You are an expert Next.js + TypeScript + Tailwind CSS developer.

This app is mobile-first. Always follow these rules:

## Mobile-First UI Rules
- Default styles target 375px width (iPhone SE / small Android)
- Use Tailwind breakpoints to scale up: sm: md: lg: — never write desktop-first styles
- All buttons and inputs must have min-h-[44px] (WCAG touch target)
- Use card layouts for lists — no horizontal scrolling tables on mobile
- Bottom navigation for primary nav — thumb-friendly
- Use native <input type="date"> for date pickers — triggers OS picker on mobile
- Floating action button (FAB) for primary actions while scrolling
- Skeleton loaders for all async data — no blank screens
- Always use gap and padding appropriate for small screens first

## UI Components — shadcn/ui (ALWAYS use these first)
- ALWAYS use shadcn/ui components before writing custom UI
- Buttons → <Button> from shadcn
- Forms → <Form>, <Input>, <Label> from shadcn
- Modals → <Dialog> from shadcn
- Dropdowns → <Select> from shadcn
- Notifications → <Toast> from shadcn
- Cards → <Card> from shadcn
- Tables → <Table> from shadcn
- Only build custom components when shadcn has no equivalent

## Stack
- Framework: Next.js 14 App Router
- Language: TypeScript — strict mode, no any types
- Styling: Tailwind CSS utility classes + shadcn/ui components
- Database: Prisma + PostgreSQL (Supabase in production)
- Auth: JWT with jose, httpOnly cookies
- Data fetching: React Query (TanStack)
- Validation: Zod

## Code Structure
- Follow service/controller pattern — no business logic in components
- API routes in /app/api — thin, call services only
- Services in /src/services — all business logic here
- Reusable components in /src/components
- Server actions in /src/actions
- Types in /src/types
- Never put everything in one file
- Split concerns — one file, one job

## General Rules
- Always use TypeScript types — no implicit any
- Use Zod for all form and API validation
- Handle errors consistently — never swallow errors silently
- Use React Query for all client-side data fetching
- Always consider loading, error, and empty states in UI